TIME(1)                          User Commands                         TIME(1)

NAME
       time - run programs and summarize system resource usage

SYNOPSIS
       time [OPTION] COMMAND [ARG]...

DESCRIPTION
       Run COMMAND with arguments ARG...  When it finishes, time writes
       a message to standard error giving timing statistics about the
       program run.

OPTIONS
       -f FORMAT, --format=FORMAT
              specify output format, overriding the format specified
              in the environment variable TIME

       -o FILE, --output=FILE
              write the resource use statistics to FILE instead of stderr

       -a, --append
              with -o, append instead of overwriting

       -p, --portability
              use the portable output format (POSIX):
              real %e\nuser %U\nsys %S

       -v, --verbose
              give very verbose output about all resources tracked

       --quiet
              don't report the status of the program even if it differs
              from zero

       -V, --version
              output version information and exit

       --help display this help and exit

   FORMAT SPECIFIERS:
       %E     elapsed real time (wall clock) in [hours:]minutes:seconds

       %e     elapsed real time in seconds

       %S     total CPU-seconds used by the system on behalf of the
              process (kernel mode)

       %U     total CPU-seconds of user-mode execution

       %P     percentage of CPU this job got (%U + %S) / %E

       %M     maximum resident set size of the process in Kbytes

       %x     exit status of the command

       %C     name and command-line arguments of the command

       %%     a literal %

       The default format is:
              %C: %es real, %Us user, %Ss sys

EXIT STATUS
       Returns the exit status of the timed command.  If the command
       was killed by a signal, returns 128 + signal number.  On internal
       errors, returns 1.

AUTHORS
       LikeOS-64 project.

SEE ALSO
       ps(1), top(1)

